<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06306140 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06306140 </ACCESS><LEADPARA>  Ten Americans and South Africa's government- owned armaments company werecharged Thursday with illegally shipping U.S.-built weapons and technology toSouth Africa, including artillery fuses later sent on to Iraq and used againstU.S. troops in the gulf war. A federal grand jury in Philadelphia also accusedJames H. Guerin, chief executive of the Pennsylvania company allegedly at thecenter of the scheme, of engaging in massive money-laundering and fraud tofalsely inflate the company's sales, costs and profits before it merged withBritain's third-largest defense contractor in 1987.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Front  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  ARMS EXPORTS TO S. AFRICA ALLEGED  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  National News in Brief  </MEMO><BYLINE>  Mercury News Wire Services  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   911101  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Friday  </DAY><MONTH>  November  </MONTH><PG.COL>  4A  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  96  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Friday, November 1, 199100306140,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>